# [AIPREF](../wg/aipref.html)

## Summary
The AIPREF working group met to provide a status update on the current state of its drafts and to coordinate efforts leading up to the upcoming interim meeting in Toronto. The group is currently focused on "pairing down" the scope of its work to reach a consensus on core semantics, specifically refining the vocabulary for expressing AI preferences after a previous Working Group Last Call (WGLC) did not result in completion. The chairs emphasized focusing on a "Minimum Viable Product" (MVP) to establish a baseline before considering more complex extensions.

## Key Discussion Points

*   **Draft Status and Scoping:** 
    *   The editors of [draft-ietf-aipref-vocab](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-aipref-vocab/) and [draft-ietf-aipref-attach](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-aipref-attach/) have removed several contentious terms to focus on refining the core semantics of the vocabulary.
    *   **Mark Knodel** noted that previous attempts to include terms like "AI output" (preferences for how data is treated in model outputs) and "inference-time usage" fell apart under scrutiny. The group is now waiting for substantive new proposals to address these areas.
    *   **Martin Thomson** confirmed that while minor edits regarding conformance are ongoing, major progress is stalled pending these new proposals.

*   **Search and AI Integration:**
    *   The group discussed the "search carve-out"—the desire for content to be indexed by search engines but excluded from AI training.
    *   There is increasing technical complexity in this distinction, as most modern search engines utilize AI "under the covers." The discussion is shifting toward whether controls should focus on AI specifically or more broadly on how data is presented in search results (e.g., in chatbots vs. traditional links).

*   **Use Cases and Wiki:**
    *   To move the discussion forward and avoid "talking at cross-purposes," the chairs have established a Wiki page to collect use cases.
    *   Use cases are categorized into three areas: **Training**, **Use**, and **Presentation**.
    *   **Mark Knodel** emphasized that the focus must remain on the *expression of preferences*, as technical enforcement is out of scope for the current charter.

*   **General User Preferences (IEEE Coordination):**
    *   **Benjamin Curtis** raised the possibility of aligning AIPREF's work with a broader IEEE standard regarding general user preferences (e.g., cookie banners, terms of service).
    *   **Mark Knodel** and **Suresh Krishnan** acknowledged the interest but cautioned that the IETF work is a "minefield" regarding user agency and the open web (e.g., assistive technologies). They encouraged Benjamin to share the draft on the mailing list but reiterated the group's current focus on a "minimal viable product" (MVP).

*   **Interim Meeting Preparation:**
    *   The group will hold a three-day interim meeting in Toronto in April. 
    *   **Suresh Krishnan** urged participants to bring up issues and proposals on the mailing list well in advance of the meeting to allow for "soak time" and ensure the high-bandwidth face-to-face time is used for resolution rather than initial discovery.

## Decisions and Action Items
*   **Decision:** The working group will focus on a "Minimum Viable Product" (MVP) for the core vocabulary and attachment drafts before exploring more complex usage preferences.
*   **Action Item:** Participants are encouraged to submit specific use cases to the new Wiki page, focusing on preferences for training, use, and presentation.
*   **Action Item:** Any new technical proposals for the Toronto interim should be submitted to the mailing list substantially before the meeting.

## Next Steps
*   **April Interim Meeting:** A three-day session in Toronto to resolve open issues in [draft-ietf-aipref-vocab](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-aipref-vocab/) and [draft-ietf-aipref-attach](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-aipref-attach/).
*   **Mailing List Discussion:** Continued refinement of terms around search, display, and purpose-based preferences.